SIMPLE: swoop
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swoop
<hw>Swoop</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Swooped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swooping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>swopen</ets>, usually,
to sweep, As. <ets>sw⟦amac⟧pan</ets> to sweep, to rush; akin to G.
<ets>schweifen</ets> to rove, to ramble, to curve, OHG.
<ets>sweifan</ets> to whirl, Icel. <ets>sveipa</ets> to sweep; also to
AS. <ets>sw⟦imac⟧fan</ets> to move quickly. Cf. <er>Sweep</er>,
<er>Swift</er>, <pos>a.</pos> & <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Swipe</er>,
<er>Swivel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fall on at once and seize;
to catch while on the wing; <as>as, a hawk <ex>swoops</ex> a
chicken</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To seize; to catch up; to take with a
sweep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now at last you came to <qex>swoop</qex> it all.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The grazing ox which <qex>swoops</qex> it [the medicinal herb] in
with the common grass.</q> <rj><qau>Glanvill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swoop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swoop
<hw>Swoop</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To descend with closed
wings from a height upon prey, as a hawk; to stoop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pass with pomp; to sweep.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swoop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swoop
<hw>Swoop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A falling on and seizing, as the prey
of a rapacious bird; the act of swooping.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The eagle fell, . . . and carried away a whole litter of cubs at a
<qex>swoop</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swoopstake</ent>⟦br⟧
